We need more context, like an error message. That guide is 5 years old, so there could be a lot of things wrong with it. For example:

  1. WPILib requires C++20 now, not C++17, so the -std flag needs to be updated.
  2. GCC 10+ or Clang 10+ is required for C++20. aarch64-linux-android-4.9 implies a really old version of either compiler, so hopefully the Android NDK has moved on from that.
  3. A lot of WPILib files have moved around, which invalidates a lot of the manual patches; you’ll have to recreate them. libuv moved to wpinet and is now managed by an upstream_utils script. LLVM moved to here and is now managed by this script. You can modify the thirdparty files in-place just to get something working in the meantime.
